Companion Blueprint 1 — Plato’s Timaeus
Source identification

Work: Plato, Timaeus
Likely date: late Plato, usually placed after the Republic and near Critias / Laws territory.
Public access: Use Jowett via Project Gutenberg / Online Library of Liberty, and Bury via Perseus/ToposText for passage checking. Public-domain access is available.

Why this is first for Imaginarium:
Timaeus is the master source for reality as a crafted rendering: a divine craftsman, eternal model, mathematical soul-structure, cosmic body, elemental geometry, astral gods, incarnation, perception, disorder, and the soul’s return to its proper circuit. Stanford summarizes the core: the cosmos is produced by a rational, purposive, beneficent Demiurge who imposes mathematical order on preexistent disorder by looking to an eternal model.
Structural map
Section	Stephanus	Function
Frame after the Republic	17a–20c	Links ideal city to cosmic myth; asks for the city to be seen “in motion.”
Atlantis / ancient Athens prelude	20c–27b	Political myth before cosmological myth; memory, catastrophe, sacred history.
Method: likely account	27c–29d	Establishes that cosmology is not exact science but a “likely story.”
Demiurge and model	29d–31b	Cosmos made beautiful by imitation of eternal intelligible pattern.
World body	31b–34b	The universe as one visible living animal.
World soul	34b–37c	Mathematical construction of cosmic soul; Same, Different, Being.
Time and heavenly bodies	37c–40d	Time as moving image of eternity; planets/stars as divine time-keepers.
Created gods and human souls	40d–44d	Lesser gods fashion mortal creatures; souls assigned to stars.
Embodiment and disorder	44d–47e	Incarnation disturbs soul-circuits; perception and necessity.
Receptacle / chōra	48a–53c	Strange “third kind”: matrix, nurse, space, field of becoming.
Elemental geometry	53c–61c	Fire, air, water, earth as geometric bodies.
Perception and physiology	61c–76e	Sensation, body, organs, disease logic.
Mortal soul and passions	69c–73d	Tripartite embodied soul: reason, spirit, appetite.
Medicine, disorder, care	81e–89d	Disease, imbalance, psychic hygiene.
Return / reordering	89d–92c	Restore soul-circuits by contemplating cosmic order; transmigration ladder.
Coverage clusters
1. Rendering ontology: copy, model, maker

Owns: 27c–31b
Core claim: visible reality is an image generated by reference to an intelligible pattern.
Imaginarium use: world as rendered copy, not brute object.

2. The cosmos as living image

Owns: 31b–34b
Core claim: the universe is a single ensouled animal, not a dead container.
Use: cosmos as organism; no hard split between physics and psyche.

3. World soul as mathematical interface

Owns: 34b–37c
Core claim: soul is the mediating structure that lets intelligible order become cosmic movement.
Use: soul as rendering engine.

4. Time, planets, astral pedagogy

Owns: 37c–40d
Core claim: time is generated through celestial motion; stars/planets teach order.
Use: astrology dashboard foundation, but objective/cosmic rather than personal-flattery astrology.

5. Incarnation as disruption of circuits

Owns: 41d–47e
Core claim: embodiment shakes the rational circuits of the soul; perception begins in turbulence.
Use: ordinary consciousness as disordered rendering.

6. Chōra / receptacle

Owns: 48a–53c
Core claim: becoming requires a strange third thing: not form, not copy, but matrix.
Use: imaginal substrate, rendering-field, dream-space, subtle receptivity.

7. Sacred geometry of matter

Owns: 53c–61c
Core claim: elements are not “stuff” first; they are patterned geometries.
Use: alchemy, sacred geometry, computational physics bridge.

8. Psychic medicine and return

Owns: 81e–92c
Core claim: disorder is treated by rebalancing body and soul through rhythm, proportion, and contemplation.
Use: practice as re-rendering.

