Best Imaginarium use

Timaeus gives the cosmos as rendered order.
Phaedrus gives the soul as winged memory trying to return to that order.

Its project formula:

ordinary speech misleads → daimon interrupts → divine madness opens → beauty reminds → wings regrow → rhetoric becomes soul-leading → writing becomes reminder, not substitute → prayer seals the transformation.

For the Imaginarium system, this is one of the best sources for designing essays, images, and videos not merely as “content,” but as psychagogic devices: forms that lead the soul from flat perception back toward living memory.

Companion Blueprint 3 — Plato’s Symposium
Source identification

Work: Plato, Symposium
Stream: Platonic eros, beauty, ascent, daimonic mediation, philosophical initiation
Public access: Jowett’s translation is available through Project Gutenberg; Fowler’s public-domain Loeb translation is available through ToposText/Perseus.

Why this matters for Imaginarium:
Timaeus gives cosmic rendering. Phaedrus gives winged erotic recollection. Symposium gives the initiatory ladder of desire: love begins in embodied attraction, becomes care for beauty, births virtue and discourse, then ascends toward Beauty itself.

Core formula:

desire → lack → mediation → generativity → ascent → vision of Beauty → Socrates as embodied daimonic proof.

Structural map
Section	Stephanus	Function
Framing chain of memory	172a–174a	The dialogue is already mediated through retelling; philosophy arrives through remembered transmission.
Socrates’ delay/trance	174a–175e	Socrates pauses in inward absorption before entering the feast.
Banquet setup	176a–178a	Instead of heavy drinking, they agree to praise Eros.
Phaedrus’ speech	178a–180b	Eros as ancient god and source of courage/honor.
Pausanias’ speech	180c–185c	Common vs heavenly love; ethical discrimination of eros.
Eryximachus’ speech	185c–188e	Eros as cosmic harmony in medicine, music, seasons, sacrifice.
Aristophanes’ speech	189a–193e	Split beings seek lost wholeness; myth of original spherical humans.
Agathon’s speech	194e–197e	Eros as youthful, beautiful, delicate, virtuous god.
Socrates questions Agathon	198a–201c	Dialectic breaks ornamental praise: love desires what it lacks.
Diotima’s teaching	201d–212a	Eros as daimon, child of Poverty and Resource, ascent to Beauty itself.
Alcibiades’ entrance	212c–222b	Drunken encomium to Socrates; Socrates as Silenus, satyr, erotic initiator.
Closing scene	222c–223d	Comedy, tragedy, philosophy, wakefulness; Socrates remains lucid.
Section functions
1. Framing memory: philosophy as transmitted initiation

172a–174a

The dialogue does not begin directly. It is told through a chain of recollection. This matters: the Symposium itself is a remembered event, almost like an oral mystery report.

Imaginarium use: transmission is never raw data. The source arrives through memory, selection, voice, and retelling.

2. Socrates’ trance before the feast

174a–175e

Socrates stops in a neighbor’s porch, absorbed in thought. He enters late.

Function: marks Socrates as someone who can withdraw from ordinary social time.
Imaginarium use: before erotic discourse begins, Socrates demonstrates altered attention.

3. Phaedrus: eros as heroic honor

178a–180b

Phaedrus praises Eros as ancient and socially ennobling. Love makes people brave because they want to appear noble before the beloved.

Function: first level of eros: shame, honor, heroic courage.
Risk: too civic and external; eros is still tied to reputation.

4. Pausanias: common and heavenly eros

180c–185c

Pausanias introduces discrimination: not every love is noble. There is lower/common love and higher/heavenly love.

Function: eros becomes ethically differentiated.
Imaginarium use: not every attraction is a portal; some binds downward, some educates upward.

5. Eryximachus: eros as cosmic medicine

185c–188e

The physician expands eros into the whole cosmos: body, health, music, seasons, sacrifice. Love becomes harmony and proportion.

Function: shifts eros from interpersonal desire to universal ordering principle.
Bridge: this is the strongest Symposium link back to Timaeus: cosmic order, proportion, body, music.

6. Aristophanes: the myth of lost wholeness

189a–193e

Aristophanes gives the famous myth of original spherical beings split apart, each seeking its lost half.

Function: eros as nostalgia for wholeness.
Imaginarium use: ordinary desire as a distorted memory of ontological incompletion.

Overlap warning: do not let this become the whole Symposium. It is vivid, but Diotima will transform eros beyond “finding your other half.”

7. Agathon: beautiful but false praise

194e–197e

Agathon praises Eros as young, beautiful, delicate, just, temperate, brave, wise.

Function: rhetoric at maximum aesthetic polish, but conceptually unstable.
Imaginarium use: beautiful language can still misrender reality.

8. Socrates’ refutation: love desires what it lacks

198a–201c

Socrates questions Agathon until the key reversal appears: love is not itself beautiful and good in the simple way Agathon claimed; love desires beauty and goodness because it lacks them.

Function: dialectical stripping of projection.
Imaginarium use: desire is not possession; it is a vector.

9. Diotima: Eros as daimonic mediator

201d–204c

Diotima teaches that Eros is not a god but a daimon, between mortal and immortal, poverty and resource, ignorance and wisdom. Stanford’s overview notes that in the Symposium, Socrates appears as both lover of wisdom and disturber of erotic norms, while Diotima’s teaching reconfigures eros as a philosophical ascent.

Function: the whole work turns here.
Imaginarium use: eros is not merely a feeling; it is a mediating intelligence between lack and plenitude.

10. Diotima: birth in beauty

204d–209e

Love seeks not simply beauty but generation in beauty: bodily children, virtues, laws, poems, teachings, institutions, and forms of soul-birth.

Function: eros becomes creativity and transmission.
Imaginarium use: desire should become generative work, not consumption.

11. Diotima: ladder of love

210a–212a

The ascent moves from one beautiful body, to all beautiful bodies, to beautiful souls, to laws and practices, to knowledge, and finally Beauty itself. Modern summaries usually identify this as the “ladder of love,” a staged ascent from particular beauty toward Beauty itself.

Function: gives the initiatory architecture.
Imaginarium use: image → pattern → soul → law/order → knowledge → source-form.

12. Alcibiades: Socrates as living icon

212c–222b

Alcibiades interrupts the metaphysical ascent with a dramatic portrait of Socrates. Socrates appears ugly outside, divine inside: a Silenus figure containing sacred images.

Function: tests the theory in embodied form.
Imaginarium use: the true image may be grotesque or comic outside but full of divine figures within.

13. Closing scene: philosophy outlasts intoxication

222c–223d

The others fall asleep; Socrates remains awake, speaking of tragedy and comedy, then leaves calmly.

Function: philosophy as sobriety within festival.
Imaginarium use: eros culminates not in frenzy alone, but in lucid wakefulness.

