Author: Apuleius of Madaurus, 2nd-century Middle Platonist
Stream: Middle Platonism, daimonology, Socratic guidance, mediation between gods and humans
Public access: Public-domain translations are available through Internet Archive, Wikisource/Perseus catalog records, and older collected editions of Apuleius’ philosophical works.

Why this matters for Imaginarium:
This is the next crucial source after Plato and Plotinus because it gives a systematic Middle Platonic account of daimons as mediating intelligences. In Plato’s Symposium, Eros is a daimonic mediator. In Phaedrus, Socrates’ daimonic sign interrupts false speech. Apuleius turns that scattered Platonic material into a full daemonology.

Core formula:

gods above → humans below → daimons in the middle → prayer, dreams, omens, inspiration, conscience, and ritual traffic pass through them → Socrates’ daimon becomes the model of personal divine guidance.

