Source-traceability notes

Use public-domain translations for broad reading, especially the older collected philosophical works of Apuleius available through Internet Archive. For exact Latin/translation comparison, the Perseus catalog record identifies an English version in a 1910 G. Bell collected edition.


For modern framing, use recent scholarly summaries carefully and paraphrase rather than importing copyrighted commentary. A BMCR review is useful for confirming the Platonic source-line from Symposium and the minister/messenger role of daimons.
Best Imaginarium use

Apuleius’ On the God of Socrates should become Imaginarium’s clean source for the daimonic middle.

Its project formula:

the gods are too high and humans too embodied for a flat cosmos → the middle air is alive with rational subtle beings → daimons carry prayers, dreams, omens, warnings, and divine messages → Socrates’ daimon shows personal guidance as a sacred inhibitory intelligence → only a purified, disciplined soul can receive the signal cleanly.

Use this text to prevent the daimon from becoming vague self-help language. In Apuleius, the daimon is not just “my intuition.” It is a precise Middle Platonic interface-being: atmospheric, rational, affective, mediating, and ethically demanding.

Companion Blueprint 8 — Corpus Hermeticum
Source identification

Work: Corpus Hermeticum
Attributed author: Hermes Trismegistus
Stream: Hermetic gnosis, divine mind, cosmic revelation, rebirth, ascent, astrology-adjacent cosmology, sacred speech
Priority tractates: CH I, IV, VII, X, XI, XIII, XVI
Public access: G. R. S. Mead’s public-domain translation is available online; Sacred Texts hosts the Mead translation and notes it is public domain.

Historical frame: These are Greek religious-philosophical Hermetic writings from Roman Egypt, often dated broadly to the first few centuries CE. A Harvard Center for the Study of World Religions note summarizes CH I as part of a group of 17 dialogues and locates the texts in Roman Egypt, roughly 100–300 CE.

Why this matters for Imaginarium:
The Corpus Hermeticum is the major source for mind as divine origin, humanity as cosmic-microcosmic being, and salvation as awakened noetic rebirth.

Core formula:

Mind reveals → cosmos appears as living divine order → human being falls into embodied fascination → ignorance binds → gnosis awakens → rebirth occurs in Nous → the soul ascends through cosmic powers → speech becomes hymn.

Structural map of the priority tractates
Tractate	Title / theme	Function for Imaginarium
CH I	Poimandres	Visionary revelation, cosmogenesis, Anthropos, fall, ascent
CH IV	The Cup / Monad	God sends a cup of Mind; humans must choose noetic awakening
CH VII	The Greatest Evil among Men is Ignorance of God	Ignorance as intoxication/sleep; conversion as sobering vision
CH X	The Key	Summary tractate: soul, mind, cosmos, rebirth, immortality
CH XI	Mind Unto Hermes	God as all-containing Mind; imagination stretched to cosmic scale
CH XIII	Secret Sermon on the Mountain	Rebirth, silence, hymnody, transformation of faculties
CH XVI	Definitions of Asclepius to King Ammon	Gods, cosmos, sun, daimons, images, cosmic administration
Section functions
CH I — Poimandres

Function: flagship revelation text. Hermes receives a visionary disclosure from Poimandres, often rendered as divine Mind or Shepherd of Men. It gives cosmogony, the divine human, the fall into nature, and the ascent through planetary/cosmic powers.

Imaginarium use:
This is the Hermetic equivalent of a total visionary operating system.

Key elements:

vision in altered/noetic state
divine Mind as revealer
light and darkness
cosmic formation
Anthropos as divine human
fall through love of nature
seven rulers / cosmic powers
ascent after death
final hymn-like proclamation

Essay ownership: CH I should own the main “Hermetic cosmogenesis and ascent” essay.

CH IV — The Cup / Monad

Function: explains why not all humans possess awakened Mind in the same way. God sends down a “cup” of Nous; those who immerse themselves in it receive gnosis.

Imaginarium use:
The cup is a perfect symbol of noetic initiation: not information, but participation in Mind.

Key elements:

Mind as divine gift
choice between bodily life and noetic life
cup / mixing bowl / baptismal image
awakening as immersion into Nous

Essay ownership: initiation into Mind.

CH VII — Ignorance as greatest evil

Function: short, fierce conversion text. Ignorance is not lack of facts; it is a drunken, sleep-like condition of being turned away from God.

Imaginarium use:
This is one of the cleanest Hermetic sources for ordinary consciousness as intoxicated rendering.

Key elements:

ignorance as evil
embodied sleep / intoxication
call to sobriety
seeing God as cure

Essay ownership: deconditioning, sobriety, awakening.

CH X — The Key

Function: a summary and doctrinal consolidation. Mead’s notes describe CH X as presenting itself as a summary or abridgement of earlier general sermons.

Imaginarium use:
Use this as the structural “Hermetic doctrine map”: God, cosmos, mind, soul, immortality, rebirth.

Key elements:

mind and soul
cosmos as living being
human dignity and danger
rebirth / immortality
the good and the beautiful

Essay ownership: Hermetic metaphysical summary.

CH XI — Mind Unto Hermes

Function: expands the imagination until it can contemplate God as all-containing Mind. The student is asked to think beyond body, place, time, and limitation.

Imaginarium use:
This is the source for noetic imagination as a disciplined expansion beyond ordinary scale.

Key elements:

God as Mind
all things held in divine consciousness
imaginative expansion as contemplative method
simultaneity, totality, non-locality

Essay ownership: cosmic imagination and divine Mind.

CH XIII — Secret Sermon on the Mountain

Function: rebirth dialogue between Hermes and Tat. The transformation is not mere belief; the old faculties are replaced by divine powers, ending in secret hymnody.

Imaginarium use:
This is the strongest Hermetic source for re-rendering the human system from within.

Key elements:

rebirth
silence
purification of irrational torments
arrival of divine powers
hymn of regeneration
transmission from father/teacher to son/student

Essay ownership: rebirth as inner replacement of faculties.

CH XVI — Definitions of Asclepius to King Ammon

Function: more cosmological and administrational. It covers gods, daimons, sun, cosmic hierarchy, and sacred images. It is especially useful for bridging Hermeticism with daimonology, theurgy, and astrological cosmic order.

Imaginarium use:
This is a bridge tractate: Hermetic cosmology becomes ritual/cosmic administration.

Key elements:

sun as cosmic governor
daimons and divine powers
images and divine presence
gods, cosmos, hierarchy
Egyptian theological flavor

Essay ownership: cosmic administration, sun, daimons, sacred image.

