113–165	Intellect / being / life	Noetic architecture.
166–183	Soul	Soul as mediator between intellect and body.
184–211	Particular souls / descent	Individual souls, embodiment, return.
Section functions
1. Unity before multiplicity

Props. 1–6

Every multiplicity depends on unity. The many cannot explain itself as mere aggregation.

Imaginarium use: any rendered world requires a unifying principle before its parts can appear as a world.

2. Causes exceed effects

Props. 7–13

A cause is greater than what it produces. Effects reveal causes, but do not exhaust them.

Imaginarium use: an image can disclose its source, but the source is always more than the image.

3. Participation

Props. 14–20

Lower beings exist by participating in higher principles. Participation is the bridge between transcendence and presence.

Imaginarium use: symbols, images, souls, planets, and bodies can contain presence without being identical to the source.

4. Procession and reversion

Props. 21–39

Everything proceeds from its cause, remains rooted in it, and returns toward it. This is the central Proclean engine.

Imaginarium formula:
remaining → proceeding → returning.

This is the cleanest metaphysical pattern for the whole Path of Re-Rendering.

5. Self-constitution

Props. 40–52

Higher realities are self-constituted: their being and activity are internally grounded.

Imaginarium use: higher intelligence is not assembled from lower mechanisms.

6. Eternity and time

Props. 53–65

Proclus distinguishes eternal being from temporal unfolding. Stanford notes that Proclus treats eternity and time in Elements propositions 53–55 and also in his Timaeus commentary.

Imaginarium use: time is not the final container; it is a lower mode of participation in higher order.

7. Henads / gods

Props. 66–112

This is Proclus’ great difference from simpler Neoplatonic summaries. Above intellect are divine unities or henads. They are not just concepts but gods as unitary sources.

Imaginarium use: divine plurality without losing unity.

Warning: do not flatten henads into archetypes. They are supra-intellectual divine unities.

8. Being, life, intellect

Props. 113–165

Proclus unfolds the noetic realm in ordered triads: being, life, intellect. Reality is structured as living intelligibility.

Imaginarium use: the intelligible world is not a static diagram; it is alive, active, and self-knowing.

9. Soul

Props. 166–183

Soul mediates between intellect and the embodied world. It receives higher order and unfolds it into motion, life, and time.

Imaginarium use: soul is the rendering mediator.

10. Particular souls and descent

Props. 184–211

The final propositions treat individual souls, their descent, embodiment, and relation to return.

Imaginarium use: the human being is a descended participant in a vast hierarchy, capable of reversion.

