Source-traceability notes

Use Taylor or other public-domain online versions for broad access, and use Dodds’ edition only for careful checking where accessible. The work has 211 propositions, and its medieval influence includes the Arabic Book of Causes, later Latinized and misattributed to Aristotle.

Stanford is useful for context, especially Proclus’ treatment of eternity/time and his broader extant works, including Elements, Platonic Theology, and the Timaeus commentary.
Best Imaginarium use

Proclus’ Elements of Theology should become Imaginarium’s source for the metaphysical operating system of hierarchy and return.

Clean formula:

the many depend on unity → causes exceed effects → lower things participate in higher principles → everything remains in its cause, proceeds from it, and returns to it → divine henads ground plurality → intellect gives living form → soul mediates form into time and embodiment → particular souls descend without severing their source → practice is reversion.

This is the end of the first ten-source arc: from Plato’s cosmic image, erotic ascent, and cave-conversion, through Plotinus’ emanation, Porphyry’s symbolic cave, Apuleius’ daimonic middle, Hermetic rebirth, Chaldean theurgy, and finally Proclus’ full metaphysical architecture.

