Companion Blueprint 12 — Proclus’ Commentary on Plato’s Timaeus
Source identification

Work: Proclus, Commentary on Plato’s Timaeus
Author: Proclus, 412–485 CE
Stream: late Neoplatonic cosmology, Platonic physics, world soul, demiurgy, time, celestial gods, mythic exegesis
Public access: Thomas Taylor’s 1820 public-domain translation is available through Internet Archive and Online Books. Modern Cambridge translations are copyrighted, so use them only for orientation where previews/reviews are available.

Scope warning: Proclus’ extant commentary reaches only up to Timaeus 44d, not the whole dialogue. Stanford’s Proclus bibliography lists the commentary as extending “up to 44d.”
Why this matters for Imaginarium

Plato’s Timaeus gives the cosmos as crafted living order. Proclus turns that into a full Neoplatonic cosmological engine:

intelligible model → demiurgic intellect → divine classes → world soul → cosmic body → time → planets → human soul’s descent into embodied disorder.

Use this as the high-resolution expansion of the earlier Timaeus blueprint.

Structural map
Commentary zone	Plato passage	Function
Proem / method	opening	Why Plato’s physics exceeds ordinary natural science
Socratic state / Atlantis frame	17a–27b	Political order and cosmic order mirror each other
Likely account	27c–29d	Cosmology as symbolic-probable discourse
Demiurge and paradigm	29d–31b	Divine intellect orders from eternal model
Cosmic body	31b–34b	Universe as one visible living god
World soul	34b–37c	Mathematical psychic structure of cosmos
Time and eternity	37c–39e	Time as moving image of eternity
Celestial gods	39e–40d	planets/stars as divine visible powers
Human soul and descent	41a–44d	souls assigned to stars; embodiment disturbs circuits
Coverage clusters
1. Plato’s physics as sacred science

Owns: Proem
Use: physics is theology in cosmological form. Stanford notes that Proclus argues Plato’s Timaeus physics is superior to Aristotelian-style natural science.

2. Mythic-political frame

Owns: 17a–27b
Use: Atlantis and the ideal city are not detachable intro fluff; political order prepares cosmic order.

3. Likely account as symbolic method

Owns: 27c–29d
Use: cosmology speaks probabilistically because it concerns generated image, not pure intelligible being.

4. Demiurgic intellect

Owns: 29d–31b
Use: the Demiurge is not a craftsman in time but divine ordering intellect.

5. Cosmos as visible god

Owns: 31b–34b
Use: the world is one living image, not dead matter.

6. World soul mathematics

Owns: 34b–37c
Use: soul as the mathematical mediator binding Same, Different, and Being into cosmic motion.

7. Time, eternity, and celestial measure

Owns: 37c–39e
Use: time is rendered eternity, not the ultimate container.

8. Celestial gods / astrology bridge

Owns: 39e–40d
Use: planets and stars as visible gods, not merely physical rocks.

9. Human soul descent

Owns: 41a–44d
Use: embodiment disrupts psychic circuits; practice must restore cosmic alignment.

Refined essay sequence
1. Physics as Theology in Disguise

Passages: Proem / opening method
Plan:

Proclus treats Timaeus as sacred physics.
Natural science is not enough if it ignores divine causes.
The cosmos must be read through cause, soul, intellect, and gods.
Imaginarium angle: physics becomes symbolic theology of rendering.
2. The City Before the Cosmos

Passages: 17a–27b
Plan:

The dialogue begins with the ideal city and Atlantis.
Proclus reads political order as preparation for cosmic order.
The well-ordered soul/city can receive the well-ordered cosmos.
Avoid treating Atlantis as conspiracy bait; keep it symbolic-political.
3. The Likely Story as Cosmological Interface

Passages: 27c–29d
Plan:

Generated things cannot receive the same discourse as eternal things.
Cosmology is image-discourse: rigorous but not absolute.
This becomes a theory of symbolic modelling.
Imaginarium angle: maps of rendered reality must know their own mode.
4. The Demiurge as Ordering Intellect

Passages: 29d–31b
Plan:

Demiurge looks to the eternal paradigm.
Proclus intensifies this through Neoplatonic hierarchy.
Creation is not arbitrary making but intellectual ordering.
Bridge to Elements: causes exceed effects; lower participates in higher.
5. The Cosmos as One Visible God

Passages: 31b–34b
Plan:

The universe is one living whole.
Cosmic body is unified, beautiful, and ensouled.
This defends the world against dead-mechanism and world-hatred.
Bridge to Plotinus II.9.
6. The World Soul as Rendering Engine

Passages: 34b–37c
Plan:

Same, Different, Being become psychic mathematics.
Soul mediates intelligible order into cosmic motion.
This is the deepest “rendering” layer in the text.
Use diagrams later: circles, ratios, bands, crossing motions.
7. Time as the Moving Image of Eternity

Passages: 37c–39e
Plan:

Eternity is whole presence; time is moving image.
Celestial motion measures temporal order.
Time is cosmic pedagogy.
Imaginarium angle: time is a divine display layer.
8. Planets as Visible Gods

Passages: 39e–40d
Plan:

Proclus reads stars/planets theologically.
Celestial bodies are divine signs and powers.
This is the proper bridge to astrology: not daily mood slop, but visible divine order.
Bridge to Greenbaum/Ficino later.
9. Souls Assigned to Stars

Passages: 41a–42d
Plan:

Human souls are distributed according to celestial order.
Star-assignment gives cosmic origin and responsibility.
This is a crucial daimon/vocation bridge.
Do not over-import later natal astrology, but mark the continuity.
10. Embodiment as Disturbed Circuitry

Passages: 42d–44d
Plan:

Incarnation shakes the soul’s circles.
Perception, body, and necessity disrupt rational motion.
Education/practice must restore the circuits to cosmic rhythm.
Imaginarium angle: ordinary consciousness is misaligned cosmic circuitry.
Cut / merge / split decisions

Keep separate:

Demiurge and world soul. Demiurge orders; world soul mediates and animates.
Time and celestial gods. Time is metaphysical image; planets are divine visible administrators.
Star-assignment and embodiment. One gives origin; the other gives disturbance.

Merge if shorter:

Time + celestial gods can merge into “cosmic clocks and visible gods.”
Star-assignment + embodiment can merge into “soul descent.”

Split if expanding:

World soul mathematics deserves a mini-series.
Demiurge can split into paradigm, intellect, and divine classes.
Celestial gods can split into fixed stars, planets, and time-measure.
Overlap warnings
Proclus vs Plato: keep Plato’s passage ownership clear, then show Proclus’ intensification.
Proclus vs Plotinus: Proclus is more hierarchic, theological, and systematic.
Astronomy vs astrology: Proclus’ celestial gods are not modern horoscope content.
Atlantis: do not drift into modern Atlantis speculation.
Likely account: do not use it as “Plato says it’s just a myth.” It is a precise claim about discourse appropriate to becoming.
